          "body": "Verse 8 is the chapter's most theologically devastating moment, precisely because it sounds acceptable on its surface. 'The word of the LORD which you have spoken is good,' Hezekiah says. That sounds like submission. Then the narrator opens the parenthesis: 'For he thought, \"For there will be peace and truth in my days.\"' The 'good' he is affirming is not the justice of God's verdict, not the faithfulness of the covenant, not the certainty of divine sovereignty. It is the personal calculation that the judgment will not fall within his lifetime. Compare this to Hezekiah's response to the Assyrian threat: he spread the threatening letter before the LORD in prayer (37:14-20). Compare it to his response to his own death sentence: he turned his face to the wall and wept bitterly (38:2-3). In both earlier crises, the suffering was his own, and he interceded with full force. In Isaiah 39, the suffering falls on his descendants, and he accepts the verdict with equanimity. The contrast is the chapter's pastoral point: it is relatively easy to pray when you are the one suffering. The test of genuine faith is whether you grieve the same way over suffering that will come to others."
